INSERT INTO card (pageId, title, description, imageUrl, orderIndex, showOnHomepage) VALUES
(1, 'Unit 1 – Cloud Concepts Overview', 'AWS Unit 1 introduces the fundamental concepts of cloud computing and explains how cloud technology is transforming the way organizations build and manage IT infrastructure. Instead of relying on physical servers and on-premises data centers, cloud computing allows businesses to access computing resources over the internet.\n\nCloud computing provides flexible, scalable, and cost-efficient solutions for storing data, running applications, and managing infrastructure. This unit focuses on understanding what the cloud is, why it is beneficial, and how AWS plays a role in delivering cloud services globally.', '', 0, 1),
(1, 'Introduction to Cloud Computing', 'Cloud computing is the delivery of computing services—such as servers, storage, databases, networking, and software—over the internet. Instead of owning and maintaining physical hardware, users can access these resources on demand from cloud providers like AWS.\n\nThis model allows organizations to quickly scale resources up or down depending on their needs, removing the need for large upfront investments in hardware and reducing the complexity of managing infrastructure.\n\nService Models:\n\n- IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service) – Virtualized computing resources such as Amazon EC2.\n\n- PaaS (Platform as a Service) – Managed platforms for building applications.\n\n- SaaS (Software as a Service) – Fully managed applications accessed over the internet.', '', 1, 0),
(1, 'Advantages of the Cloud', 'Cloud computing offers several key advantages compared to traditional on-premises systems.\n\nKey Benefits:\n\n- Scalability – Instantly increase or decrease resources based on demand.\n\n- Cost Efficiency – Pay only for what you use instead of buying hardware upfront.\n\n- Availability & Reliability – Built-in redundancy across multiple data centers.\n\n- Global Reach – Deploy applications closer to users around the world to reduce latency.', '', 2, 0),
(1, 'Introduction to AWS', 'Amazon Web Services (AWS) is one of the leading cloud service providers in the world, offering a wide range of services including compute, storage, databases, networking, analytics, and machine learning.\n\nAWS operates on a global infrastructure made up of Regions and Availability Zones. Regions are geographic areas, while Availability Zones are isolated data centers within a region designed for fault tolerance and high availability.\n\nAWS uses a pay-as-you-go pricing model, meaning users are charged only for the resources they consume, making it accessible to both startups and large enterprises.', '', 3, 0),
(1, 'AWS Global Infrastructure', 'AWS infrastructure is designed for high availability and reliability. Each Region contains multiple Availability Zones that are physically separated but connected with high-speed networking.\n\nThis design allows applications to be distributed across multiple locations so that if one data center fails, others can continue operating. AWS also uses edge locations to deliver content quickly to users worldwide, improving performance for latency-sensitive applications.', '/Pictures/Unit 1.png', 4, 0),
(1, 'Moving to the AWS Cloud', 'Migrating to the AWS cloud involves transferring applications, data, and workloads from on-premises systems to AWS infrastructure. This allows organizations to gain scalability, flexibility, and cost savings.\n\nThe “6 R’s” of Migration:\n\n- Rehosting (lift and shift)\n\n- Replatforming\n\n- Repurchasing\n\n- Refactoring\n\n- Retiring\n\n- Retaining', '', 5, 0),
(1, 'Benefits of Cloud Migration', 'Moving to the cloud provides greater flexibility, enabling faster deployment of applications and quicker responses to changing business needs. Disaster recovery improves because data can be replicated across multiple locations.\n\nBy spending less time managing physical infrastructure, organizations can focus more on innovation—developing new features, improving user experience, and experimenting with new ideas.', '', 6, 0),
(1, 'Shared Responsibility Model', 'AWS uses a shared responsibility model to define how security duties are divided between AWS and the customer.\n\nResponsibilities:\n\n- AWS is responsible for security of the cloud (infrastructure, hardware, and facilities).\n\n- Customers are responsible for security in the cloud (applications, data, configurations, and access).', '', 7, 0),
(1, 'Unit 1 Summary', 'AWS Unit 1 introduces the core concepts of cloud computing and explains how cloud services provide scalable, reliable, and cost-efficient solutions for modern applications.\n\nCloud computing removes the need for physical infrastructure and allows organizations to access resources on demand. AWS provides a global platform for delivering these services, supported by Regions, Availability Zones, and edge locations.\n\nUnderstanding these concepts is essential for building and managing cloud-based systems and sets the foundation for all future AWS topics.', '', 8, 0),
(2, 'Unit 2 – Cloud Economics and Billing', 'AWS Unit 2 focuses on how cloud computing impacts costs and how organizations manage and optimize spending in AWS. Unlike traditional IT infrastructure, where companies must invest heavily in hardware upfront, cloud computing uses a pay-as-you-go pricing model that allows businesses to pay only for what they use.\n\nThis unit explores how pricing works in AWS, how organizations calculate the total cost of using cloud services, and how tools like AWS Billing and AWS Organizations help manage costs across multiple accounts.', '', 0, 1),
(2, 'Fundamentals of Pricing', 'AWS pricing is based on consumption, meaning users only pay for the resources they actually use. This helps organizations avoid overpaying for unused infrastructure and align their costs with demand.\n\nKey Pricing Models:\n\n- On-Demand – Pay for compute or storage by the second or hour with no long-term commitment.\n\n- Reserved Instances / Savings Plans – Commit to usage over time in exchange for lower prices.\n\n- Spot Instances – Use spare capacity at a discount for flexible, interruption-tolerant workloads.\n\nCost Drivers:\n\n- Compute time (e.g., EC2 instances).\n\n- Storage usage (e.g., S3, EBS volumes).\n\n- Data transfer (especially outbound traffic).\n\n- Requests and API calls.', '/Pictures/Unit 2.png', 1, 0),
(2, 'Total Cost of Ownership (TCO)', 'Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) refers to the full cost of running infrastructure over time, not just the initial purchase price. Traditional environments must account for hardware, maintenance, electricity, cooling, and staffing.\n\nIn AWS, TCO is often lower because there are no upfront hardware costs, maintenance is handled by AWS, infrastructure scales automatically, and unused resources can be turned off.\n\nOrganizations use TCO calculations to compare on-premises costs with cloud-based solutions and determine whether moving to the cloud is financially beneficial.', '', 2, 0),
(2, 'AWS Organizations', 'AWS Organizations allows businesses to manage multiple AWS accounts under a single structure. Instead of managing accounts individually, organizations can group them and apply policies at scale.\n\nThis improves cost tracking, security, and management efficiency across large environments.\n\nKey Features:\n\n- Consolidated Billing – Combines billing across all accounts.\n\n- Organizational Units (OUs) – Group accounts logically by team, department, or environment.\n\n- Service Control Policies (SCPs) – Apply permission guardrails across accounts.', '', 3, 0),
(2, 'AWS Billing & Cost Management', 'AWS Billing tools help organizations track, manage, and analyze spending so they can understand where their money is going.\n\nImportant Tools:\n\n- AWS Billing Dashboard – High-level view of current charges and usage.\n\n- Cost Explorer – Visualizes spending patterns over time.\n\n- Budgets – Set spending limits and alerts when thresholds are exceeded.\n\n- Cost Allocation Tags – Label resources to track costs by project, team, or environment.', '', 4, 0),
(2, 'Cost Optimization Strategies', 'AWS provides many strategies to reduce costs and improve efficiency.\n\nCost optimization is an ongoing process that requires monitoring, analysis, and adjustments.\n\nCommon Techniques:\n\n- Right-Sizing – Choose instance sizes that match workload needs.\n\n- Auto Scaling – Automatically adjust capacity based on demand.\n\n- Reserved Pricing – Use Reserved Instances or Savings Plans for predictable workloads.\n\n- Spot Instances – Use for flexible, fault-tolerant tasks.\n\n- Storage Tiering – Move cold data to cheaper tiers such as S3 Glacier.', '', 5, 0),
(2, 'Shared Financial Responsibility', 'While AWS provides cost-efficient infrastructure, customers are responsible for how they use resources. Poor configuration or leaving unused resources running can quickly increase costs.\n\nCustomer Responsibilities:\n\n- Monitor usage regularly.\n\n- Turn off or delete unused resources.\n\n- Choose the right pricing models for each workload.\n\n- Optimize storage and compute utilization.', '', 6, 0),
(2, 'Unit 2 Summary', 'AWS Unit 2 explains how cloud computing changes the way organizations manage costs. Instead of paying upfront for hardware, AWS allows users to pay only for what they use.\n\nUnderstanding pricing models, TCO, AWS Organizations, and billing tools helps organizations control spending and avoid unnecessary expenses. By applying cost optimization strategies, businesses can maximize value while minimizing cloud costs.', '', 7, 0),
(3, 'Unit 3 – AWS Global Infrastructure', 'AWS Unit 3 focuses on the global infrastructure that allows AWS to deliver cloud services reliably and efficiently around the world. Cloud computing depends heavily on physical data centers, networking systems, and geographic distribution to ensure high availability and performance.\n\nAWS has one of the largest global infrastructures, consisting of Regions, Availability Zones, and Edge Locations. This structure allows applications to run closer to users, reduce latency, and maintain availability even when failures occur.', '', 0, 1),
(3, 'AWS Global Infrastructure', 'AWS global infrastructure refers to the physical and virtual systems that support AWS services worldwide, including data centers, networking, and locations that host cloud resources.\n\nIt is designed to provide high availability, support fault tolerance, deliver low latency, and enable global scalability by distributing resources across multiple geographic areas.', '/Pictures/Unit 3.png', 1, 0),
(3, 'AWS Regions', 'An AWS Region is a geographic area that contains multiple data centers. Each Region is isolated from others to improve fault tolerance and security.\n\nUsing multiple Regions can improve disaster recovery and ensure applications remain available during large-scale outages.\n\nChoosing a Region:\n\n- Proximity to users to reduce latency.\n\n- Compliance and data residency requirements.\n\n- Service availability and feature support.\n\n- Cost differences between Regions.', '', 2, 0),
(3, 'Availability Zones (AZs)', 'Availability Zones are isolated data centers within a Region. They are physically separated but connected with high-speed, low-latency networking.\n\nAZs are designed so that failures in one zone do not affect others. By deploying resources across multiple AZs, organizations can build highly available systems that continue running even if one data center fails.', '', 3, 0),
(3, 'Edge Locations', 'Edge locations are smaller data centers located closer to end users. They are primarily used for content delivery and caching through services like Amazon CloudFront.\n\nDelivering content from edge locations reduces latency, improves user experience, and enables fast global content delivery instead of sending data from a single central Region.', '', 4, 0),
(3, 'High Availability & Fault Tolerance', 'AWS infrastructure is designed to support both high availability and fault tolerance.\n\nUsing multiple AZs and Regions, along with redundant networking and storage, helps applications stay online even during failures.\n\nKey Concepts:\n\n- High Availability – Systems are designed to remain operational with minimal downtime by using multiple AZs and Regions.\n\n- Fault Tolerance – Systems can continue operating even when components fail through redundancy and automatic failover.', '', 5, 0),
(3, 'AWS Services Overview', 'AWS offers many services that run on top of its global infrastructure. These services are organized into categories based on their function.\n\nMajor Service Categories:\n\n- Compute – Run applications (e.g., EC2, Lambda).\n\n- Storage – Store and manage data (e.g., S3, EBS).\n\n- Database – Manage structured and unstructured data (e.g., RDS, DynamoDB).\n\n- Networking – Connect resources and manage traffic (e.g., VPC, Route 53).\n\n- Security – Protect systems and data (e.g., IAM, KMS).', '', 6, 0),
(3, 'Unit 3 Summary', 'AWS Unit 3 explains how AWS uses a global network of Regions, Availability Zones, and Edge Locations to deliver cloud services efficiently.\n\nRegions provide geographic separation, AZs enable high availability, and edge locations improve performance for users worldwide. Understanding this infrastructure is essential for designing systems that can handle failures, scale globally, and deliver consistent performance.', '', 7, 0),
(4, 'Unit 4 – AWS Cloud Security', 'AWS Unit 4 focuses on how security works in the cloud and how organizations protect their systems, data, and users. Security is one of the most important parts of cloud computing because everything—from applications to sensitive data—is hosted online.\n\nAWS provides built-in tools and best practices to help secure cloud environments. However, security is not handled entirely by AWS. Instead, AWS uses a shared responsibility model, where both AWS and the customer play a role in keeping systems secure.', '', 0, 1),
(4, 'AWS Shared Responsibility Model', 'The AWS Shared Responsibility Model defines how security duties are divided between AWS and the user.\n\nAWS is responsible for security OF the cloud, which includes:\n\n- Physical data centers\n- Hardware and networking infrastructure\n- Global cloud systems\n\nCustomers are responsible for security IN the cloud, which includes:\n\n- Managing users and permissions\n- Protecting data\n- Configuring services correctly\n- Updating operating systems and applications\n\nThis model ensures that AWS handles the infrastructure, but users must properly secure their own resources.', '', 1, 0),
(4, 'AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM)', 'AWS IAM is the main service used to control access in AWS. It allows organizations to define who can access resources and what actions they are allowed to perform.\n\nIAM includes:\n\n- Users – Individual identities\n- Groups – Collections of users with shared permissions\n- Roles – Temporary access with specific permissions\n- Policies – JSON rules that define permissions\n\nA key concept in IAM is the principle of least privilege, meaning users only get access to what they need. This reduces security risks and prevents unauthorized actions.\n\nIAM is essential for securing AWS environments and is used in almost every service.', '', 2, 0),
(4, 'Securing a New AWS Account', 'When creating a new AWS account, it is critical to set up security immediately to prevent unauthorized access.\n\nImportant steps include:\n\n- Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for the root user\n- Avoid using the root account for daily tasks\n- Create IAM users for regular access\n- Set strong password policies\n- Enable billing alerts\n\nThese steps help ensure that the account is protected from the start and reduce the risk of security breaches.', '', 3, 0),
(4, 'Securing AWS Accounts', 'Securing AWS accounts involves managing access and monitoring activity to prevent threats.\n\nBest practices include:\n\n- Use IAM roles instead of sharing credentials\n- Regularly rotate passwords and access keys\n- Monitor login activity and API usage\n- Limit permissions using least privilege\n- Use security groups and network rules\n\nContinuous monitoring and updating of security settings are important to maintain a strong security posture.', '', 4, 0),
(4, 'Securing Data in AWS', 'Protecting data is a critical part of cloud security. AWS provides tools to secure data both at rest and in transit.\n\nMethods include:\n\nEncryption:\n- Data at rest can be encrypted using AWS KMS\n- Data in transit is protected using HTTPS and TLS\n\nAccess Control:\n- IAM policies control who can access data\n- Permissions prevent unauthorized usage\n\nBackup & Recovery:\n- Data can be backed up and replicated\n- Helps protect against data loss\n\nBy combining encryption, access control, and backups, organizations can ensure their data remains secure.', '', 5, 0),
(4, 'Monitoring & Security Tools', 'AWS provides several services to monitor and detect security threats.\n\nKey tools include:\n\n- AWS CloudTrail – Tracks user activity and API calls\n- Amazon CloudWatch – Monitors performance and triggers alerts\n- Amazon GuardDuty – Detects threats using machine learning\n- AWS Security Hub – Centralizes security alerts\n\nThese tools help organizations detect unusual behavior and respond quickly to potential threats.', '', 6, 0),
(4, 'Working to Ensure Compliance', 'Compliance means following laws, regulations, and security standards required for handling data.\n\nAWS supports compliance by:\n\n- Providing secure infrastructure\n- Offering certifications (HIPAA, SOC, ISO, etc.)\n- Giving tools for auditing and monitoring\n\nOrganizations are responsible for:\n\n- Configuring services correctly\n- Protecting sensitive data\n- Keeping records of activity\n\nCompliance requires ongoing monitoring and regular audits to ensure standards are maintained.', '', 7, 0),
(4, 'Security Best Practices', 'Important AWS security best practices include:\n\n- Enable MFA for all accounts\n- Use least privilege permissions\n- Encrypt sensitive data\n- Monitor activity continuously\n- Regularly update credentials and policies\n\nFollowing these practices helps reduce risks and protect cloud environments.', '', 8, 0),
(4, 'Unit 4 Summary', 'AWS Unit 4 explains how cloud security works and how responsibilities are shared between AWS and users. While AWS secures the infrastructure, customers must secure their data, applications, and access.\n\nServices like IAM help manage permissions, while encryption and monitoring tools protect data and detect threats. Compliance and best practices ensure systems remain secure over time.\n\nUnderstanding these concepts is essential for building safe and reliable cloud systems.', '', 9, 0),
(5, 'Unit 5 – Networking & Content Delivery', 'AWS Unit 5 focuses on cloud networking, how virtual networks are built using Amazon VPC, how traffic flows through subnets and route tables; and how AWS delivers content globally using Route 53 and CloudFront. The goal of this unit is to understand how AWS resources communicate, how to control access using networking rules, and how to improve performance using content delivery services.', '', 0, 1),
(5, 'Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)', 'Amazon VPC is a logically isolated virtual network in AWS where you can launch resources like EC2 instances. It is similar to having your own private data center in the cloud.\n\nYou control:\n\n- IP address ranges (CIDR blocks)\n\n- Subnets\n\n- Route tables\n\n- Internet gateways\n\n- Security rules\n\nNote: Every AWS account comes with a default VPC, but you can create custom VPCs for better security and organization.', '/Pictures/VPC.png', 1, 0),
(5, 'Subnets', 'A subnet is a smaller network inside a VPC. Each subnet exists in only one Availability Zone.\n\nTypes of subnets:\n\n- Public subnet - has a route to an Internet Gateway\n\n- Private subnet - no direct internet access\n\nNote: Subnets are used to organize workloads and improve security.', '', 2, 0),
(5, 'Route Tables', 'Route tables control how traffic is directed within your VPC and to external networks.\n\nCommon routes:\n\n- Local - Internal VPC traffic\n\n- 0.0.0.0/0 - internet traffic\n\nNote: If a route table is misconfigured, resources may not be reachable.', '/Pictures/Demo.png', 3, 0),
(5, 'CIDR & IP Addressing', 'CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) defines the IP address range for your VPC and subnets.\n\nThe /16 means there are 65,536 IP addresses.\n\nExample: 10.0.0.0/16\n\nNote: CIDR blocks cannot be changed after creation.', '', 4, 0),
(5, 'Security Groups', 'Security Groups are virtual firewalls for EC2 instances that control inbound and outbound traffic.\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Stateful - return traffic is automatically allowed\n\n- Applied at the instance level\n\n- Can have multiple security groups per instance\n\nNote: Security Groups are the primary way to control network access to your instances.', '', 5, 0),
(5, 'Route 53', 'Route 53 is AWS''s DNS (Domain Name System) service.\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Domain registration\n\n- DNS routing\n\n- Health checks\n\nNote: Routing policies include simple, weighted, latency, Failover, and geolocation.', '/Pictures/Transit.png', 6, 0),
(5, 'Unit 5 Summary', 'AWS Unit 5 focuses on networking and content delivery.\n\nKey Points:\n\n- Amazon VPC provides isolated networks\n\n- Subnets divide networks\n\n- Route tables control traffic\n\n- Security Groups and NACLs provide security\n\n- Route 53 handles DNS and domain management\n\n- CloudFront delivers content globally', '', 7, 0),
(6, 'Unit 6 – Compute Services', 'AWS Unit 6 concentrates on compute services, which define how applications run in the cloud. Compute services deliver processing power, memory, and execution environments for applications. This unit delves into different compute models, including virtual machines, containers, managed platforms, and serverless computing. It explains how AWS enables developers to balance control, cost, and operational responsibility.', '', 0, 1),
(6, 'Amazon EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)', 'Amazon EC2 provides resizable virtual servers in the cloud. Users can launch virtual machines that scale up or down based on demand, eliminating the need to purchase and maintain physical servers.\n\nService Model: EC2 is classified as Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS).\n\nResponsibility Split:\n\n- AWS manages the underlying hardware\n\n- Customers are responsible for the operating system, applications, and configurations', '/Pictures/EC2.png', 1, 0),
(6, 'EC2 - How It Works', 'When an EC2 instance is launched, AWS provisions a virtual machine with the specified configuration.\n\nProcess:\n\n- Select an Amazon Machine Image (AMI)\n\n- Choose an instance type\n\n- Configure security groups and networking\n\n- Launch the instance', '', 2, 0),
(6, 'EC2 - Instance Types', 'EC2 offers multiple instance families, each optimized for different workloads.\n\nInstance Families:\n\n- General purpose instances: Offer balanced resources\n\n- Compute-optimized instances: Focus on performance\n\n- Memory-optimized instances: Designed for large in-memory databases\n\n- Storage-optimized instances: Provide fast disk access', '/Pictures/instance types.png', 3, 0),
(6, 'EC2 - Benefits & Use Cases', 'EC2 is ideal for applications that require full control over the server.\n\nBenefits:\n\n- Supports custom software stacks\n\n- Compatible with legacy applications\n\n- Handles specialized workloads\n\nCommon Use Cases:\n\n- Web servers\n\n- Application servers\n\n- Development environments', '', 4, 0),
(6, 'EC2 Cost Optimization', 'AWS provides multiple pricing models to help reduce compute costs. Cost optimization focuses on matching options to specific needs.\n\nPricing Models:\n\n- On-Demand: Pay for compute capacity by the hour or second\n\n- Reserved Instances: Significant discount for 1-3 year commitments\n\n- Spot Instances: Use spare capacity at up to 90% discount\n\n- Savings Plans: Flexible pricing model with lower costs', '/Pictures/price patterns.png', 5, 0),
(6, 'Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service)', 'Amazon ECS is a fully managed container orchestration platform that allows developers to run and manage containers.\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Fully managed service\n\n- Supports Docker containers\n\n- Automatic scaling\n\n- Integrated with other AWS services', '', 6, 0),
(6, 'Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service)', 'Amazon EKS runs Kubernetes on AWS, making it easy to deploy, manage, and scale containerized applications.\n\nIdeal For:\n\n- Teams already using Kubernetes\n\n- Requiring portability across environments\n\n- Need for Kubernetes-native features', '', 7, 0),
(6, 'AWS Fargate', 'AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine specifically for containers. It eliminates the need to manage EC2 instances or clusters.\n\nBenefits:\n\n- No server management required\n\n- Pay only for resources used\n\n- Automatic scaling\n\n- Works with both ECS and EKS', '', 8, 0),
(6, 'AWS Lambda', 'AWS Lambda is a serverless compute service that runs code in response to events without provisioning or managing servers.\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Event-driven execution\n\n- Automatic scaling\n\n- Pay per request\n\n- No server management', '', 9, 0),
(6, 'AWS Elastic Beanstalk', 'AWS Elastic Beanstalk is a Platform as a Service (PaaS) for application deployment. Developers upload their code, and AWS automatically manages the infrastructure.\n\nManaged Aspects:\n\n- Scaling\n\n- Monitoring\n\n- Load balancing\n\n- Application health monitoring', '', 10, 0),
(6, 'Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store)', 'Amazon EBS provides persistent block storage volumes for use with EC2 instances. EBS volumes are highly available and reliable storage volumes that can be attached to any running instance in the same Availability Zone.\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Persistent storage independent of instance lifecycle\n\n- High availability and durability\n\n- Multiple volume types for different use cases\n\n- Automatic backups with snapshots', '/Pictures/EBS.png', 11, 0),
(6, 'Service Comparison', 'Different compute services offer varying levels of control and management responsibility.\n\nControl vs. Management:\n\n- EC2: Offers the most control but requires the most management effort\n\n- Containers (ECS, EKS, Fargate): Improve portability and efficiency\n\n- Lambda: Provides the lowest operational overhead with event-driven execution\n\n- Elastic Beanstalk: Balances ease of use with infrastructure control', '', 12, 0),
(7, 'Unit 7 – Storage Services', 'AWS Unit 7 focuses on cloud storage in AWS, explaining how data is stored, accessed, protected, and managed across different AWS storage services. Storage is a critical component of cloud computing because applications rely on fast, reliable, and scalable data access.\n\nThis unit explores the four main storage types used in AWS: block storage, object storage, file storage, and archival storage. Each storage type serves a different purpose depending on performance needs, scalability requirements, cost considerations, and how often the data is accessed. By the end of this unit, you should be able to choose the most appropriate storage service for a given workload.', '', 0, 1),
(7, 'Storage Basics', 'Storage in AWS is designed to be scalable, durable, and highly available , meaning it can grow as data increases, protect against data loss, and remain accessible even during failures. AWS provides multiple storage services because no single storage solution fits every application.\n\nDifferent applications require different access speeds, sharing capabilities, and cost models. For example, operating systems and databases need low-latency storage, while backups and archives prioritize durability and low cost. Understanding these differences allows organizations to store data efficiently while minimizing cost and maximizing performance.', '', 1, 0),
(7, 'Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store)', 'Amazon EBS is a block storage service designed specifically for use with Amazon EC2 instances. It functions like a virtual hard drive that can be attached to an instance and used to store operating systems, applications, and databases.\n\nEBS provides persistent storage , meaning data remains available even if the EC2 instance is stopped or restarted. This makes EBS ideal for workloads that require consistent performance and reliable data persistence.', '/Pictures/EBS.png', 2, 0),
(7, 'EBS – How It Works', 'EBS volumes are created within a specific Availability Zone and can only be attached to EC2 instances in the same zone. Each volume acts as raw block-level storage, allowing the operating system to format and manage it just like a physical disk.\n\nVolumes can be detached from one instance and reattached to another, which is useful for recovery or maintenance. AWS also supports EBS snapshots, which create point-in-time backups stored in Amazon S3 for durability and disaster recovery.', '', 3, 0),
(7, 'EBS – Volume Types', 'Amazon EBS offers multiple volume types optimized for different workloads. SSD-backed volumes are designed for frequent access, low latency, and high IOPS, making them suitable for databases and application servers.\n\nHDD-backed volumes are optimized for large, sequential workloads such as log processing or data warehousing. Choosing the correct volume type helps balance performance and cost, ensuring applications run efficiently without overpaying for unused performance.', '', 4, 0),
(7, 'Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service)', 'Amazon S3 is an object storage service designed to store and retrieve virtually unlimited amounts of data. Instead of storing data as files or blocks, S3 stores data as objects inside containers called buckets.\n\nS3 is built for extreme durability (99.999999999%), global accessibility, and scalability. It is commonly used for backups, static website hosting, media storage, and large-scale data analytics.', '', 5, 0),
(7, 'S3 – Objects & Buckets', 'Each S3 object consists of the data itself, metadata, and a unique key that identifies the object within a bucket. Buckets must have globally unique names and define where data is stored.\n\nS3 supports features such as versioning , which keeps multiple versions of an object, and encryption , which protects data at rest. These features make S3 both flexible and secure for storing critical data.', '/Pictures/bucket.png', 6, 0),
(7, 'S3 – Storage Classes', 'Amazon S3 provides multiple storage classes to reduce cost based on access frequency. S3 Standard is used for frequently accessed data, while Standard-IA and One Zone-IA are designed for infrequently accessed data at a lower cost.\n\nS3 Intelligent-Tiering automatically moves data between tiers based on usage patterns, and S3 Glacier is used for long-term archival storage. Storage classes allow organizations to optimize cost without sacrificing durability.', '', 7, 0),
(7, 'S3 – Use Cases', 'Amazon S3 is commonly used for:\n\nBecause S3 is highly scalable and accessible over the internet, it is often the backbone of cloud-based applications.\n\n- Application data storage\n\n- Backups and disaster recovery\n\n- Static website hosting\n\n- Media storage and streaming\n\n- Data lakes and analytics', '', 8, 0),
(7, 'Amazon EFS (Elastic File System)', 'Amazon EFS is a file storage service that provides a shared file system for multiple EC2 instances. Unlike EBS, which attaches to one instance at a time, EFS allows simultaneous access from many instances.\n\nEFS automatically scales as files are added or removed, eliminating the need for capacity planning. This makes it ideal for workloads that require shared access to files.', '', 9, 0),
(7, 'EFS – How It Works', 'EFS uses standard file system protocols, allowing applications to access files just like they would on a traditional file server. Storage capacity grows and shrinks automatically based on usage.\n\nBecause EFS spans multiple Availability Zones, it provides high availability and fault tolerance without manual configuration.', '', 10, 0),
(7, 'EFS – Benefits', 'EFS is well suited for collaborative workloads such as:\n\nIts ability to support shared access simplifies application architecture and improves scalability.\n\n- Content management systems\n\n- Web servers with shared content\n\n- Development and testing environments\n\n- Machine learning workflows', '', 11, 0),
(7, 'Amazon S3 Glacier – Use Cases', 'Amazon S3 Glacier is a low-cost archival storage service designed for data that is rarely accessed but must be retained for long periods. Retrieval times range from minutes to hours depending on the retrieval option selected.\n\nGlacier is commonly used for compliance records, long-term backups, and historical archives. While access is slower, the significantly lower storage cost makes it ideal for long-term retention.', '', 12, 0),
(7, 'Storage Comparison', 'Choosing the right storage service depends on performance needs, access patterns, and budget.\n\n- EBS: Block storage for EC2 with low latency and high performance\n\n- S3: Object storage that is highly scalable, durable, and internet accessible\n\n- EFS: File storage that supports shared access across multiple instances\n\n- S3 Glacier: Archival storage optimized for low cost and infrequent access', '', 13, 0),
(8, 'Unit 8 – Database Services', 'AWS Unit 8 focuses on database services, explaining how structured data is stored, queried, and managed at scale. Databases are essential for applications that require fast access to organized data, such as user accounts, transactions, analytics, and reporting systems.\n\nThis unit explores different types of databases including relational databases , NoSQL databases , data warehouses , and cloud-native relational databases. Each service is designed for specific workloads, performance needs, and scalability requirements. By the end of this unit, you should be able to choose the most appropriate database service for a given workload.', '', 0, 1),
(8, 'Database Basics', 'Databases store structured or semi-structured data in a way that allows it to be efficiently queried, updated, and managed. Unlike simple file storage, databases support indexing, relationships, and optimized queries. AWS provides multiple database services because applications have different needs .\n\nSome applications require strict consistency and immediate updates, while others need massive scalability and flexible data models. Understanding the difference between relational and NoSQL databases is critical for selecting the right database service for your workload.', '', 1, 0),
(8, 'Amazon RDS (Relational Database Service)', 'Amazon RDS is a managed relational database service that supports popular database engines such as MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, and SQL Server. It is designed for easy setup, operation, and scaling. It automates tasks such as hardware provisioning, database setup, patching, and backups. It is ideal for familiar SQL-based databases.', '/Pictures/RDS.png', 2, 0),
(8, 'Amazon Aurora', 'Aurora is a fully managed relational database built by AWS and compatible with MySQL and PostgreSQL. It combines the familiarity of traditional databases with the performance and reliability that cloud-native services bring. Aurora offers high availability, automatic scaling, and improved durability compared to traditional RDS engines.', '/Pictures/Aurora.png', 3, 0),
(8, 'RDS - How It Works', 'With Amazon RDS, AWS manages the underlying infrastructure, operating system, and database software. Users interact with the databases through standard SQL queries, just as they would with a traditional relational database.\n\nRDS supports Multi-AZ deployment for high availability and automatic failover. AWS handles backups, software patching, and monitoring, allowing developers to focus on application development rather than database management.', '', 4, 0),
(8, 'Aurora - How It Differs from RDS', '- Unlike traditional RDS engines, Aurora separates compute and storage. This allows storage to scale transparently without downtime and improves performance.\n\n- Proactive features include automatic patching, scaling, and improved durability with replication across multiple Availability Zones.', '', 5, 0),
(8, 'RDS - Use Cases & Benefits', 'Common use cases include web applications, e-commerce platforms, transaction processing, and applications requiring reliable relational database performance.\n\nBenefits include ease of use, automated management, scalability, and reliability. RDS simplifies database administration while maintaining compatibility with existing applications.', '', 6, 0),
(8, 'Aurora - Use Cases', '- High-traffic web applications\n\n- SaaS platforms\n\n- Applications requiring high availability and managed scalability\n\n- Mobile and web applications\n\n- Gaming leaderboards\n\n- IoT applications and session management', '', 7, 0),
(8, 'Amazon Redshift', 'Amazon Redshift is a fully managed data warehouse service designed for large-scale data analytics. Unlike transactional databases, Redshift is optimized for analyzing massive datasets through parallel processing. It can handle petabytes of data and supports complex analytical queries for business intelligence and reporting.', '/Pictures/Redshift.png', 8, 0),
(8, 'Amazon DynamoDB', 'Amazon DynamoDB is a fully managed NoSQL database service designed for applications that need consistent, single-digit millisecond latency at any scale. Unlike relational databases, DynamoDB provides flexible data models and automatic scaling without the need for server management.', '/Pictures/DynamoDB.png', 9, 0),
(8, 'Database Comparison', 'Choosing the right database service depends on data structure, access patterns, scalability needs, and performance requirements.\n\n- Amazon RDS: Managed relational database service, suitable for different application requirements. By understanding the strengths and interactions of RDS, Aurora, DynamoDB, and Redshift, organizations can design data architectures that are efficient, scalable, and cost-effective.\n\n- Amazon Aurora: Cloud-native relational database with high performance, automatic scaling, and improved durability compared to traditional RDS.\n\n- Amazon DynamoDB: Serverless NoSQL database with extreme scalability and single-digit millisecond latency.\n\n- Amazon Redshift: Data warehouse optimized for analytics and reporting, designed for large-scale data processing.', '', 10, 0),
(9, 'Unit 9 – Cloud Architecture', 'AWS Unit 9 focuses on cloud architecture and the principles used to design scalable, reliable, secure, and cost-efficient systems in the cloud. Instead of simply deploying resources, architects must design systems that perform well under different conditions while remaining secure and resilient.\n\nAWS provides guidance through the AWS Well-Architected Framework, which is a set of best practices used to evaluate and improve cloud architectures. The framework helps organizations understand whether their systems follow proven design patterns and whether they can handle growth, failures, and changing workloads.\n\nBy applying the principles of the Well-Architected Framework, organizations can build systems that operate efficiently, maintain security, and adapt to future demands.', '', 0, 1),
(9, 'AWS Well-Architected Framework', 'The AWS Well-Architected Framework is a collection of architectural best practices that help organizations design and operate reliable cloud systems. It provides guidance on building infrastructure that is secure, efficient, resilient, and cost-effective.\n\nThe framework is built around several pillars, each representing a critical area of cloud architecture. These pillars provide guidelines for evaluating existing systems and improving them through continuous monitoring and design improvements.\n\nArchitects regularly review their systems against these pillars to identify weaknesses and opportunities for optimization. This process helps ensure that cloud applications remain stable, secure, and scalable as they grow.', '/Pictures/Unit 9 Pillars.png', 1, 0),
(9, 'Cloud Design Principles', 'AWS recommends several design principles when building cloud architectures. These principles guide architects in designing systems that are flexible and capable of adapting to changing workloads.\n\nOne important principle is stopping the need to guess infrastructure capacity. In traditional systems, organizations often overestimate resource needs. Cloud computing allows resources to scale automatically as demand increases.\n\nAnother principle is automation. Automating infrastructure deployment and management reduces human error and increases efficiency. Infrastructure can be defined using code, allowing systems to be deployed quickly and consistently.\n\nArchitects are also encouraged to design systems that can evolve over time. Instead of building rigid infrastructure, cloud architectures should allow services to be replaced, scaled, or improved without major disruptions.\n\nFinally, architects should measure system performance and use data to guide decisions, ensuring systems improve continuously.', '', 2, 0),
(9, 'Operational Excellence', 'The Operational Excellence pillar focuses on running and monitoring systems effectively while continually improving operational processes.\n\nOrganizations achieve operational excellence by automating routine tasks, monitoring system performance, and responding quickly to operational events. Automation reduces manual work and allows systems to scale efficiently.\n\nAnother important aspect is learning from operational experiences. Teams analyze system behavior and incidents to improve processes and prevent future problems.\n\nThis pillar encourages continuous improvement, ensuring that systems become more efficient and reliable over time.', '', 3, 0),
(9, 'Security', 'The Security pillar focuses on protecting data, applications, and infrastructure from unauthorized access or threats. Security is built into every layer of cloud architecture, including identity management, encryption, and monitoring.\n\nAWS provides tools that allow organizations to manage access using identity and access management (IAM). Encryption helps protect sensitive data both while it is stored and while it is transmitted across networks.\n\nMonitoring systems track activity and detect suspicious behavior, allowing organizations to respond quickly to security incidents.\n\nBy implementing strong security practices, organizations can protect sensitive information and maintain trust with their users.', '', 4, 0),
(9, 'Reliability', 'The Reliability pillar focuses on ensuring that systems can recover from failures and continue operating even when unexpected events occur.\n\nReliable systems use redundancy, meaning multiple components perform the same function so that if one fails, another can take over. AWS supports this by allowing resources to be distributed across multiple Availability Zones.\n\nSystems can also scale automatically when demand increases, ensuring applications remain available even during traffic spikes.\n\nAnother important concept is fault tolerance, which allows systems to continue functioning even when parts of the infrastructure fail.', '', 5, 0),
(9, 'Performance Efficiency', 'The Performance Efficiency pillar focuses on using computing resources efficiently to meet system requirements.\n\nCloud systems should select the right resources for the workload, such as choosing the appropriate instance types, storage solutions, and database services.\n\nPerformance efficiency also involves monitoring system behavior and adjusting resources when necessary. Because cloud technologies evolve rapidly, organizations should continually evaluate new services and features that may improve system performance.\n\nBy optimizing resources, organizations can ensure applications perform well while avoiding unnecessary resource usage.', '', 6, 0),
(9, 'Cost Optimization', 'The Cost Optimization pillar focuses on avoiding unnecessary costs while maximizing the value gained from cloud resources.\n\nIn cloud computing, organizations pay only for the resources they use. Monitoring usage and selecting the correct pricing models can significantly reduce costs.\n\nTechniques such as auto-scaling, resource monitoring, and choosing appropriate instance types help ensure that organizations do not overpay for unused resources.\n\nCost optimization also involves analyzing usage patterns and continuously adjusting infrastructure to match current demand.', '', 7, 0),
(9, 'AWS Trusted Advisor', 'AWS Trusted Advisor is a service that analyzes an AWS environment and provides recommendations for improving infrastructure.\n\nTrusted Advisor checks systems across several categories, including cost optimization, security, performance, reliability, and service limits.\n\nFor example, Trusted Advisor may identify unused resources that are still generating costs, security settings that could be improved, or performance issues that may affect applications.\n\nBy following these recommendations, organizations can improve system efficiency and ensure their cloud architecture follows AWS best practices.', '', 8, 0),
(9, 'Unit 9 Summary', 'AWS Unit 9 focuses on designing cloud systems using the AWS Well-Architected Framework. The framework provides guidelines for building systems that are secure, reliable, efficient, and cost-effective.\n\nThe pillars of operational excellence, security, reliability, performance efficiency, and cost optimization help organizations evaluate their architectures and improve them over time.\n\nTools such as AWS Trusted Advisor further support these principles by analyzing cloud environments and providing actionable recommendations for improvement.\n\nUnderstanding these architectural principles helps organizations build scalable and resilient systems that can adapt to changing workloads and business needs.', '', 9, 0),
(10, 'Unit 10 – Auto Scaling and Monitoring', 'AWS Unit 10 focuses on monitoring system performance and automatically scaling resources to handle changing workloads. In cloud computing environments, demand for resources can change rapidly depending on user traffic, application usage, or time of day. To maintain performance and availability, systems must be able to adjust their resources automatically.\n\nAWS provides several services that help organizations monitor infrastructure and respond to changes in demand. Services such as Amazon CloudWatch, Elastic Load Balancing, and Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling work together to maintain application performance and ensure systems remain reliable and efficient. These services allow organizations to automatically scale resources, distribute incoming traffic, and monitor system health in real time.', '', 0, 1),
(10, 'Autoscaling and Monitoring Basics', 'Monitoring and scaling are essential parts of cloud architecture. Monitoring allows organizations to track system performance, detect potential problems, and gather data about how applications behave under different workloads.\n\nAuto scaling helps ensure that applications have the right amount of computing resources at all times. When demand increases, additional resources are automatically added to handle the load. When demand decreases, resources are removed to reduce unnecessary costs.\n\nBy combining monitoring tools with automated scaling systems, AWS allows organizations to build systems that respond dynamically to changing conditions.', '', 1, 0),
(10, 'Elastic Load Balancing (ELB)', 'Elastic Load Balancing is a service that automatically distributes incoming network traffic across multiple computing resources, such as EC2 instances, containers, or IP addresses. By spreading traffic across multiple servers, load balancing improves application availability and reliability.\n\nLoad balancers ensure that no single server becomes overloaded with traffic. If one server becomes unavailable or fails, the load balancer redirects traffic to other healthy servers. This helps maintain system uptime and ensures that users continue to receive responses from the application.\n\nElastic Load Balancing also integrates with other AWS services such as Auto Scaling, allowing systems to automatically add or remove servers based on current demand.', '/Pictures/Elastic Load Balancing.png', 2, 0),
(10, 'Types of Elastic Load Balancers', 'AWS provides several types of load balancers designed for different types of traffic.\n\nApplication Load Balancer (ALB) operates at the application layer and is designed for HTTP and HTTPS traffic. It is commonly used for web applications and microservices architectures.\n\nNetwork Load Balancer (NLB) operates at the transport layer and is designed for high-performance applications requiring extremely low latency.\n\nGateway Load Balancer is used for deploying and scaling third-party network appliances such as firewalls or security monitoring tools.\n\nEach load balancer type provides different capabilities depending on the needs of the application.', '/Pictures/Uses of ELB.png', 3, 0),
(10, 'Amazon CloudWatch', 'Amazon CloudWatch is a monitoring and observability service that provides data and insights about AWS resources and applications. It collects metrics, logs, and events from AWS services and allows organizations to track system performance over time.\n\nCloudWatch helps administrators monitor CPU usage, network traffic, disk activity, and many other system metrics. By analyzing this data, organizations can identify performance issues, detect anomalies, and ensure systems are functioning properly.\n\nCloudWatch also supports alarms and notifications. When certain thresholds are reached, such as high CPU usage or increased latency, CloudWatch can trigger alerts or automated actions.', '', 4, 0),
(10, 'CloudWatch Monitoring Features', 'CloudWatch provides several powerful features that help monitor cloud environments.\n\nMetrics track performance data such as CPU utilization, memory usage, and network activity.\n\nLogs collect detailed records of application activity and system events, helping administrators troubleshoot issues.\n\nAlarms allow administrators to define thresholds that trigger notifications or automated responses when conditions change.\n\nThese features make CloudWatch an essential tool for maintaining system visibility and operational awareness.', '', 5, 0),
(10, 'Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling', 'Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling automatically adjusts the number of EC2 instances in a system based on demand. This ensures applications have enough computing capacity during high traffic while minimizing costs during periods of low usage.\n\nAuto Scaling works by monitoring system metrics such as CPU utilization or network traffic. When predefined thresholds are reached, Auto Scaling launches additional instances to handle the increased workload. When demand decreases, it terminates unnecessary instances to reduce costs.\n\nThis process ensures that applications remain responsive and efficient regardless of changes in traffic.', '/Pictures/Autoscaling.png', 6, 0),
(10, 'Auto Scaling Benefits', 'Auto Scaling provides several important benefits for cloud systems.\n\nOne key benefit is improved availability. By automatically adding instances during traffic spikes, systems can continue operating smoothly even under heavy demand.\n\nAnother benefit is cost efficiency. Organizations only pay for the resources they need at a given time because instances are automatically removed when they are no longer required.\n\nAuto Scaling also improves system resilience by replacing unhealthy instances and maintaining the desired number of running servers.', '', 7, 0),
(10, 'Integration of Monitoring and Scaling', 'Monitoring and scaling services work together to maintain system performance. CloudWatch collects metrics about system behavior and sends this data to Auto Scaling policies.\n\nWhen CloudWatch detects that system metrics exceed defined thresholds, it can trigger Auto Scaling to launch additional instances. Similarly, when usage decreases, Auto Scaling reduces the number of instances to conserve resources.\n\nElastic Load Balancing then distributes traffic across the available instances, ensuring that no single server becomes overloaded.\n\nThis integration allows AWS systems to automatically adapt to changing workloads without manual intervention.', '', 8, 0),
(10, 'Unit 10 Summary', 'AWS Unit 10 focuses on maintaining system performance through monitoring and automated scaling. Services such as Amazon CloudWatch provide visibility into system performance, while Elastic Load Balancing distributes traffic across resources to improve availability.\n\nAmazon EC2 Auto Scaling ensures that applications always have the right amount of computing capacity by automatically adding or removing instances based on demand.\n\nTogether, these services allow organizations to build highly available, scalable, and cost-efficient cloud systems that adapt automatically to changing workloads.', '', 9, 0);